# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: collision-detection-2d
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In computer graphics and computational geometry, a **bounding volume** (or **bounding region**) for a set of objects is a closed region that completely contains the union of the objects in the set.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Bounding volumes are used to improve the efficiency of geometrical operations, such as by using simple regions, having simpler ways to test for overlap.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A bounding volume for a set of objects is also a bounding volume for the single object consisting of their union, and the other way around.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Therefore, it is possible to confine the description to the case of a single object, which is assumed to be non-empty and bounded (finite).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Bounding volumes are most often used to accelerate certain kinds of tests.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In ray tracing, bounding volumes are used in ray-intersection tests, and in many rendering algorithms, they are used for viewing frustum tests.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] If the ray or viewing frustum does not intersect the bounding volume, it cannot intersect the object contained within, allowing trivial rejection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Similarly if the frustum contains the entirety of the bounding volume, the contents may be trivially accepted without further tests.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] These intersection tests produce a list of objects that must be 'displayed' (rendered; rasterized).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In collision detection, when two bounding volumes do not intersect, the contained objects cannot collide.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Testing against a bounding volume is typically much faster than testing against the object itself, because of the bounding volume's simpler geometry.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] This is because an 'object' is typically composed of polygons or data structures that are reduced to polygonal approximations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In either case, it is computationally wasteful to test each polygon against the view volume if the object is not visible.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] To obtain bounding volumes of complex objects, a common way is to break the objects/scene down using a scene graph or more specifically a bounding volume hierarchy, like e.g.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The basic idea behind this is to organize a scene in a tree-like structure where the root comprises the whole scene and each leaf contains a smaller subpart.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The precision of the intersection test is related to the amount of space within the bounding volume not associated with the bounded object, called *void space*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Sophisticated bounding volumes generally allow for less void space but are more computationally expensive.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] It is common to use several types in conjunction, such as a cheap one for a quick but rough test in conjunction with a more precise but also more expensive type.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The types treated here all give convex bounding volumes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] If the object being bounded is known to be convex, this is not a restriction.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] If non-convex bounding volumes are required, an approach is to represent them as a union of a number of convex bounding volumes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Unfortunately, intersection tests become quickly more expensive as the bounding volumes become more sophisticated.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A *bounding box* or *minimum bounding box* (*MBB*) is a cuboid, or in 2-D a rectangle, containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In dynamical simulation, bounding boxes are preferred to other shapes of bounding volume such as bounding spheres or cylinders for objects that are roughly cuboid in shape when the intersection test needs to be fairly accurate.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] It is also a basic component of the R-tree method of spatial indexing.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In many applications the bounding box is aligned with the axes of the co-ordinate system, and it is then known as an **axis-aligned bounding box** (**AABB**).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] To distinguish the general case from an AABB, an arbitrary bounding box is sometimes called an **oriented bounding box** (**OBB**), or an **OOBB** when an existing object's local coordinate system is used.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] AABBs are much simpler to test for intersection than OBBs, but have the disadvantage that when the model is rotated they cannot be simply rotated with it, but need to be recomputed.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **bounding capsule** is a swept sphere (i.e. the volume that a sphere takes as it moves along a straight line segment) containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Capsules can be represented by the radius of the swept sphere and the segment that the sphere is swept across).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] It has traits similar to a cylinder, but is easier to use, because the intersection test is simpler.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A capsule and another object intersect if the distance between the capsule's defining segment and some feature of the other object is smaller than the capsule's radius.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] For example, two capsules intersect if the distance between the capsules' segments is smaller than the sum of their radii.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] This holds for arbitrarily rotated capsules, which is why they're more appealing than cylinders in practice.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **bounding cylinder** is a cylinder containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In most applications the axis of the cylinder is aligned with the vertical direction of the scene.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Cylinders are appropriate for 3-D objects that can only rotate about a vertical axis but not about other axes, and are otherwise constrained to move by translation only.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Two vertical-axis-aligned cylinders intersect when, simultaneously, their projections on the vertical axis intersect – which are two line segments – as well their projections on the horizontal plane – two circular disks.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In video games, bounding cylinders are often used as bounding volumes for people standing upright.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **bounding ellipsoid** is an ellipsoid containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Ellipsoids usually provide tighter fitting than a sphere.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Intersections with ellipsoids are done by scaling the other object along the principal axes of the ellipsoid by an amount equal to the multiplicative inverse of the radii of the ellipsoid, thus reducing the problem to intersecting the scaled object with a unit sphere.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Care should be taken to avoid problems if the applied scaling introduces skew.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Skew can make the usage of ellipsoids impractical in certain cases, for example collision between two arbitrary ellipsoids.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A *bounding sphere* is a sphere containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Bounding spheres are represented by centre and radius.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] They are very quick to test for collision with each other: two spheres intersect when the distance between their centres does not exceed the sum of their radii.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] This makes bounding spheres appropriate for objects that can move in any number of dimensions.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **bounding slab** is the volume that projects to an extent on an axis, and can be thought of as the slab bounded between two planes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A bounding box is the intersection of orthogonally oriented bounding slabs.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **bounding triangle** in 2-D is quite useful to speedup the clipping or visibility test of a B-Spline curve.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] See "Circle and B-Splines clipping algorithms" under the subject Clipping (computer graphics) for an example of use.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **convex hull** is the smallest convex volume containing the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] If the object is the union of a finite set of points, its convex hull is a polytope.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A **discrete oriented polytope** (**DOP**) generalizes the bounding box.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A k-DOP is the Boolean intersection of extents along *k* directions.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Thus, a *k*-DOP is the Boolean intersection of *k* bounding slabs and is a convex polytope containing the object (in 2-D a polygon; in 3-D a polyhedron).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] A 2-D rectangle is a special case of a 2-DOP, and a 3-D box is a special case of a 3-DOP.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In general, the axes of a DOP do not have to be orthogonal, and there can be more axes than dimensions of space.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] For example, a 3-D box that is beveled on all edges and corners can be constructed as a 13-DOP.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The actual number of faces can be less than 2 times *k* if some faces become degenerate, shrunk to an edge or a vertex.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] For some types of bounding volume (OBB and convex polyhedra), an effective check is that of the separating axis theorem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The idea here is that, if there exists an axis by which the objects do not overlap, then the objects do not intersect.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Usually the axes checked are those of the basic axes for the volumes (the unit axes in the case of an AABB, or the 3 base axes from each OBB in the case of OBBs).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Often, this is followed by also checking the cross-products of the previous axes (one axis from each object).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In the case of an AABB, this tests becomes a simple set of overlap tests in terms of the unit axes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] An OBB is similar in this respect, but is slightly more complicated.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] For the ranges *m*,*n* and *o*,*p* it can be said that they do not intersect if *m* > *p* or *o* > *n*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Thus, by projecting the ranges of 2 OBBs along the I, J, and K axes of each OBB, and checking for non-intersection, it is possible to detect non-intersection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] By additionally checking along the cross products of these axes (I0×I1, I0×J1, ...) one can be more certain that intersection is impossible.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] This concept of determining non-intersection via use of axis projection also extends to convex polyhedra, however with the normals of each polyhedral face being used instead of the base axes, and with the extents being based on the minimum and maximum dot products of each vertex against the axes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] Note that this description assumes the checks are being done in world space.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The intersection of two *k*-DOP's can be computed very similarly to AABBs: for each orientation, you just check the two corresponding intervals of the two DOP's.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] So, just like DOP's being a generalization of AABBs, the intersection test is a generalization of the AABB overlap test.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The complexity of the overlap test of two DOP's is in O(*k*).
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] This assumes, however, that both DOP's are given with respect to the same set of orientations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] If one of them is rotated, this is no longer true.
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] In that case, one relatively easy way to check the two DOP's $D^{1},D^{2}$ for intersection is to enclose the rotated one, $D^{2}$ , by another, smallest enclosing DOP ${\tilde {D}}^{2}$ that is oriented with respect to the orientations of the first DOP $D^{1}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/bounding-volume] The procedure for that is a little bit more complex, but eventually amounts to a matrix vector multiplication of complexity O(*k*) as well.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collision detection is closely linked to calculating the distance between objects, as objects collide when the distance between them is less than or equal to zero.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Negative distances indicate that one object has penetrated another.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Performing collision detection requires more context than just the distance between the objects.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Accurately identifying the points of contact on both objects' surfaces is also essential for computing a physically accurate collision response.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The complexity of this task increases with the level of detail in the objects' representations: the more intricate the model, the greater the computational cost.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collision detection frequently involves dynamic objects, adding a temporal dimension to distance calculations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Instead of simply measuring distance between static objects, collision detection algorithms often aim to determine whether the objects' motion will bring them to a point in time when their distance is zero—an operation that adds significant computational overhead.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In collision detection involving multiple objects, a naive approach would require detecting collisions for all pairwise combinations of objects.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] As the number of objects increases, the number of required comparisons grows rapidly: for n objects, ${n(n-1)}/{2}$ intersection tests are needed with a naive approach.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This quadratic growth makes such an approach computationally expensive as n increases.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Due to the complexity mentioned above, collision detection is a computationally intensive process.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Nevertheless, it is essential for interactive applications like video games, robotics, and real-time physics engines.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] To manage these computational demands, extensive efforts have gone into optimizing collision detection algorithms.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A commonly used approach towards accelerating the required computations is to divide the process into two phases: the **broad phase** and the **narrow phase**.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The broad phase aims to answer the question of whether objects might collide, using a conservative but efficient approach to rule out pairs that clearly do not intersect, thus avoiding unnecessary calculations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Objects that cannot be definitively separated in the broad phase are passed to the narrow phase.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Here, more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If they do, the narrow phase often calculates the exact time and location of the intersection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This phase aims at quickly finding objects or parts of objects for which it can be quickly determined that no further collision test is needed.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A useful property of such approach is that it is output sensitive.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In the context of collision detection this means that the time complexity of the collision detection is proportional to the number of objects that are close to each other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] An early example of that is the I-COLLIDE where the number of required narrow phase collision tests was $O(n+m)$ where n is the number of objects and m is the number of objects at close proximity.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This is a significant improvement over the quadratic complexity of the naive approach.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Several approaches can be grouped under the spatial partitioning umbrella, which includes octrees (for 3D), quadtrees (for 2D), binary space partitioning (or BSP trees) and other, similar approaches.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If one splits space into a number of simple cells, and if two objects can be shown not to be in the same cell, then they need not be checked for intersection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Dynamic scenes and deformable objects require updating the partitioning which can add overhead.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Bounding Volume Hierarchy (BVH) is a tree structure over a set of bounding volumes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collision is determined by doing a tree traversal starting from the root.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If the bounding volume of the root doesn't intersect with the object of interest, the traversal can be stopped.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If, however there is an intersection, the traversal proceeds and checks the branches for each there is an intersection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Branches for which there is no intersection with the bounding volume can be culled from further intersection test.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Therefore, multiple objects can be determined to not intersect at once.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] BVH can be used with deformable objects such as cloth or soft-bodies but the volume hierarchy has to be adjusted as the shape deforms.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For deformable objects we need to be concerned about self-collisions or self intersections.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collision between two objects is computed by computing intersection between the bounding volumes of the root of the tree as there are collision we dive into the sub-trees that intersect.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Exact collisions between the actual objects, or its parts (often triangles of a triangle mesh) need to be computed only between intersecting leaves.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The same approach works for pair wise collision and self-collisions.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] During the broad-phase, when the objects in the world move or deform, the data-structures used to cull collisions have to be updated.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In cases where the changes between two frames or time-steps are small and the objects can be approximated well with axis-aligned bounding boxes, the sweep and prune algorithm can be a suitable approach.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The algorithm keeps track of currently intersecting boxes, and as objects move, re-sorting the intervals helps keep track of the status.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Once a pair of physical bodies has been selected for further investigation, collisions need to be checked more carefully.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] However, in many applications, individual objects (if they are not too deformable) are described by a set of smaller primitives, mainly triangles.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The obvious thing to do is to check all triangles $S_{j}$ against all triangles $T_{k}$ for collisions, but this involves $n^{2}$ comparisons, which is highly inefficient.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If possible, it is desirable to use a pruning algorithm to reduce the number of pairs of triangles that need to be checked.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The most widely used family of algorithms is known as the *hierarchical bounding volumes* method.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] As a preprocessing step, for each object (e.g., S and T ) calculates a hierarchy of bounding volumes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Then, at each time step, when collisions need to be checked between S and T , the hierarchical bounding volumes are used to reduce the number of pairs of triangles under consideration.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For simplicity, provide an example using bounding spheres, although it has been noted that spheres are undesirable in many cases.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If E is a set of triangles, a bounding sphere is pre-calculated. $B(E)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] There are many ways of choosing $B(E)$ , $B(E)$ is a sphere that completely contains E and is as small as possible.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Ahead of time, $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ can be computed.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Clearly, if these two spheres do not intersect (and that is very easy to test), then neither do S and T .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This is not much better than an *n*-body pruning algorithm, however.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Apply this to S and T , and calculate (ahead of time) the bounding spheres $B(L(S)),B(R(S))$ and $B(L(T)),B(R(T))$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The hope here is that these bounding spheres are much smaller than $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] And, if, for instance, $B(S)$ and $B(L(T))$ do not intersect, then there is no sense in checking any triangle in S against any triangle in $L(T)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] As a precomputation, take each physical body (represented by a set of triangles) and recursively decompose it into a binary tree, where each node N represents a set of triangles, and its two children represent $L(N)$ and $R(N)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] At each node in the tree, pre-compute the bounding sphere $B(N)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] When the time comes for testing a pair of objects for collision, their bounding sphere tree can be used to eliminate many pairs of triangles.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Many variants of the algorithms are obtained by choosing something other than a sphere for $B(T)$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If one chooses axis-aligned bounding boxes, one gets AABBTrees.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Oriented bounding box trees are called OBBTrees.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some trees are easier to update if the underlying object changes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some trees can accommodate higher order primitives such as splines instead of simple triangles.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In this phase, the objects under consideration are relatively close to each other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Still, attempts to quickly determine if a full intersection is needed are employed first.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This step is sometimes referred to as mid-phase.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Once these tests passed (e.g. the pair of objects may be colliding) more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Since checking whether two objects intersect can be a relatively expensive operation, one quick way to potentially avoid the computation is to check whether the bounding volumes enclosing the two objects intersect.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Bounding volumes are typically used in the early (pruning) stage of collision detection, so that only objects with overlapping volumes need be compared in detail.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If they don't overlap, there is no need to check the actual objects.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A false positive intersection in this case means that the bounding volumes intersect but the actual objects do not.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Different bounding volume types offer different trade-offs for these properties.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Axis-Align Bounding Boxes (AABB) and cuboids are popular due to their simplicity and quick intersection tests.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Bounding volumes such as Oriented Bounding Boxes (OBB), K-DOPs and Convex-hulls offer a tighter approximation of the enclosed shape at the expense of a more elaborate intersection test.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Objects for which pruning approaches could not rule out the possibility of a collision have to undergo an exact collision detection computation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] According to the separating planes theorem, for any two disjoint convex objects, there exists a plane so that one object lies completely on one side of that plane, and the other object lies on the opposite side of that plane.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This property allows the development of efficient collision detection algorithms between convex objects.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Several algorithms are available for finding the closest points on the surface of two convex polyhedral objects - and determining collision.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Lin that used a variation on the simplex algorithm from linear programming and the Gilbert-Johnson-Keerthi distance algorithm are two such examples.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] These algorithms approach constant time when applied repeatedly to pairs of stationary or slow-moving objects, and every step is initialized from the previous collision check.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The result of all this algorithmic work is that collision detection can be done efficiently for thousands of moving objects in real time on typical personal computers and game consoles.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Where most of the objects involved are fixed, as is typical of video games, a priori methods using precomputation can be used to speed up execution.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Pruning is also desirable here, both *n*-body pruning and pairwise pruning, but the algorithms must take time and the types of motions used in the underlying physical system into consideration.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] When it comes to the exact pairwise collision detection, this is highly trajectory dependent, and one almost has to use a numerical root-finding algorithm to compute the instant of impact.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] At any point in time, the two triangles can be checked for intersection using the twenty planes previously mentioned.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If $P(u,v,w)$ is the plane going through points $u,v,w$ in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ then there are twenty planes $P(v_{i}(t),v_{j}(t),v_{k}(t))$ to track.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Each plane needs to be tracked against three vertices, this gives sixty values to track.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Using a root finder on these sixty functions produces the exact collision times for the two given triangles and the two given trajectory.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If the trajectories of the vertices are assumed to be linear polynomials in t then the final sixty functions are in fact cubic polynomials, and in this exceptional case, it is possible to locate the exact collision time using the formula for the roots of the cubic.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some numerical analysts suggest that using the formula for the roots of the cubic is not as numerically stable as using a root finder for polynomials.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A triangle mesh object is commonly used in 3D body modeling.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Normally the collision function is a triangle to triangle intercept or a bounding shape associated with the mesh.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A triangle centroid is a center of mass location such that it would balance on a pencil tip.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The simulation need only add a centroid dimension to the physics parameters.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Given centroid points in both object and target it is possible to define the line segment connecting these two points.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The position vector of the centroid of a triangle is the average of the position vectors of its vertices.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Here the length/distance of the segment is an adjustable "hit" criteria size of segment.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] As the objects approach the length decreases to the threshold value.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A triangle sphere becomes the effective geometry test.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A sphere centered at the centroid can be sized to encompass all the triangle's vertices.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Physical simulators differ in the way they react on a collision.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some use the softness of the material to calculate a force, which will resolve the collision in the following time steps like it is in reality.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This is very CPU intensive for low softness materials.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some simulators estimate the time of collision by linear interpolation, roll back the simulation, and calculate the collision by the more abstract methods of conservation laws.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some iterate the linear interpolation (Newton's method) to calculate the time of collision with a much higher precision than the rest of the simulation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collision detection utilizes time coherence to allow even finer time steps without much increasing CPU demand, such as in air traffic control.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] After an inelastic collision, special states of sliding and resting can occur and, for example, the Open Dynamics Engine uses constraints to simulate them.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Constraints avoid inertia and thus instability.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Implementation of rest by means of a scene graph avoids drift.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In other words, physical simulators usually function one of two ways: where the collision is detected *a posteriori* (after the collision occurs) or *a priori* (before the collision occurs).
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In addition to the *a posteriori* and *a priori* distinction, almost all modern collision detection algorithms are broken into a hierarchy of algorithms.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Often the terms "discrete" and "continuous" are used rather than *a posteriori* and *a priori*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In the *a posteriori* case, the physical simulation is advanced by a small step, then checked to see if any objects are intersecting or visibly considered intersecting.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] At each simulation step, a list of all intersecting bodies is created, and the positions and trajectories of these objects are "fixed" to account for the collision.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This method is called *a posteriori* because it typically misses the actual instant of collision, and only catches the collision after it has actually happened.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In the *a priori* methods, there is a collision detection algorithm which will be able to predict very precisely the trajectories of the physical bodies.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The instants of collision are calculated with high precision, and the physical bodies never actually interpenetrate.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] This is called *a priori* because the collision detection algorithm calculates the instants of collision before it updates the configuration of the physical bodies.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The main benefits of the *a posteriori* methods are as follows.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In this case, the collision detection algorithm need not be aware of the myriad of physical variables; a simple list of physical bodies is fed to the algorithm, and the program returns a list of intersecting bodies.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The collision detection algorithm doesn't need to understand friction, elastic collisions, or worse, nonelastic collisions and deformable bodies.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In addition, the *a posteriori* algorithms are in effect one dimension simpler than the *a priori* algorithms.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] An *a priori* algorithm must deal with the time variable, which is absent from the *a posteriori* problem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] On the other hand, *a posteriori* algorithms cause problems in the "fixing" step, where intersections (which aren't physically correct) need to be corrected.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Moreover, if the discrete step is too large, the collision could go undetected, resulting in an object which passes through another if it is sufficiently fast or small.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The benefits of the *a priori* algorithms are increased fidelity and stability.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] It is difficult (but not completely impossible) to separate the physical simulation from the collision detection algorithm.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] However, in all but the simplest cases, the problem of determining ahead of time when two bodies will collide (given some initial data) has no closed form solution—a numerical root finder is usually involved.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some objects are in *resting contact*, that is, in collision, but neither bouncing off, nor interpenetrating, such as a vase resting on a table.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In all cases, resting contact requires special treatment: If two objects collide (*a posteriori*) or slide (*a priori*) and their relative motion is below a threshold, friction becomes stiction and both objects are arranged in the same branch of the scene graph.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Video games have to split their very limited computing time between several tasks.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Despite this resource limit, and the use of relatively primitive collision detection algorithms, programmers have been able to create believable, if inexact, systems for use in games.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For a long time, video games had a very limited number of objects to treat, and so checking all pairs was not a problem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In two-dimensional games, in some cases, the hardware was able to efficiently detect and report overlapping pixels between sprites on the screen.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In other cases, simply tiling the screen and binding each *sprite* into the tiles it overlaps provides sufficient pruning, and for pairwise checks, bounding rectangles or circles called hitboxes are used and deemed sufficiently accurate.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Three-dimensional games have used spatial partitioning methods for n -body pruning, and for a long time used one or a few spheres per actual 3D object for pairwise checks.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Exact checks are very rare, except in games attempting to simulate reality closely.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Even then, exact checks are not necessarily used in all cases.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Because games do not need to mimic actual physics, stability is not as much of an issue.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Almost all games use *a posteriori* collision detection, and collisions are often resolved using very simple rules.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For instance, if a character becomes embedded in a wall, they might be simply moved back to their last known good location.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Some games will calculate the distance the character can move before getting embedded into a wall, and only allow them to move that far.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In many cases for video games, approximating the characters by a point is sufficient for the purpose of collision detection with the environment.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In this case, binary space partitioning trees provide a viable, efficient and simple algorithm for checking if a point is embedded in the scenery or not.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Such a data structure can also be used to handle "resting position" situation gracefully when a character is running along the ground.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Collisions between characters, and collisions with projectiles and hazards, are treated separately.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A robust simulator is one that will react to any input in a reasonable way.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For instance, imagining a high speed racecar video game, it is conceivable that the cars would advance a substantial distance along the race track from one simulation step to the next.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] If there is a shallow obstacle on the track (such as a brick wall), it is not entirely unlikely that the car will completely leap over it, and this is very undesirable.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] These are the hallmarks of a failing collision detection and physical simulation system.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] *Big Rigs: Over the Road Racing* is an infamous example of a game with a failing or possibly missing collision detection system.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A **hitbox** is an invisible shape commonly used in video games for real-time collision detection; it is a type of bounding box.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] It is often a rectangle (in 2D games) or cuboid (in 3D) that is attached to and follows a point on a visible object (such as a model or a sprite).
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Circular or spheroidial shapes are also common, though they are still most often called "boxes".
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] It is common for animated objects to have hitboxes attached to each moving part to ensure accuracy during motion.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Hitboxes are used to detect "one-way" collisions such as a character being hit by a punch or a bullet.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] They are unsuitable for the detection of collisions with feedback (e.g. bumping into a wall) due to the difficulty experienced by both humans and AI in managing a hitbox's ever-changing locations; these sorts of collisions are typically handled with much simpler axis-aligned bounding boxes instead.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] Players may use the term "hitbox" to refer to these types of interactions regardless.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] A **hurtbox** is a hitbox used to detect incoming sources of damage.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] In this context, the term *hitbox* is typically reserved for those which deal damage.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] For example, an attack may only land if the hitbox around an attacker's punch connects with one of the opponent's hurtboxes on their body, while opposing hitboxes colliding may result in the players trading or cancelling blows, and opposing hurtboxes do not interact with each other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-detection] The term is not standardized across the industry; some games reverse their definitions of *hitbox* and *hurtbox*, while others only use "hitbox" for both sides.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] In the context of classical mechanics simulations and physics engines employed within video games, **collision response** deals with models and algorithms for simulating the changes in the motion of two solid bodies following collision and other forms of contact.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Two rigid bodies in unconstrained motion, potentially under the action of forces, may be modelled by solving their equations of motion using numerical integration techniques.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] On collision, the kinetic properties of two such bodies seem to undergo an instantaneous change, typically resulting in the bodies rebounding away from each other, sliding, or settling into relative static contact, depending on the elasticity of the materials and the configuration of the collision.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The origin of the rebound phenomenon, or *reaction*, may be traced to the behaviour of real bodies that, unlike their perfectly rigid idealised counterparts, do undergo minor compression on collision, followed by expansion, prior to separation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The compression phase converts the kinetic energy of the bodies into potential energy and to an extent, heat.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The expansion phase converts the potential energy back to kinetic energy.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The degree of relative kinetic energy retained after a collision, termed the *restitution*, is dependent on the elasticity of the bodies‟ materials.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The coefficient of restitution between two given materials is modeled as the ratio $e\in [0..1]$ of the relative post-collision speed of a point of contact along the contact normal, with respect to the relative pre-collision speed of the same point along the same normal.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] These coefficients are typically determined empirically for different material pairs, such as wood against concrete or rubber against wood.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Values for e close to zero indicate inelastic collisions such as a piece of soft clay hitting the floor, whereas values close to one represent highly elastic collisions, such as a rubber ball bouncing off a wall.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The kinetic energy loss is relative to one body with respect to the other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Thus the total momentum of both bodies with respect to some common reference is unchanged after the collision, in line with the principle of *conservation of momentum*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Another important contact phenomenon is surface-to-surface friction, a force that impedes the relative motion of two surfaces in contact, or that of a body in a fluid.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] In this section we discuss surface-to-surface friction of two bodies in relative static contact or sliding contact.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] In the real world, friction is due to the imperfect microstructure of surfaces whose protrusions interlock into each other, generating reactive forces tangential to the surfaces.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] To overcome the friction between two bodies in static contact, the surfaces must somehow lift away from each other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Once in motion, the degree of surface affinity is reduced and hence bodies in sliding motion tend to offer lesser resistance to motion.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] These two categories of friction are respectively termed *static friction* and *dynamic friction*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] It is a force which is applied to an object by another object or by a person.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The direction of the applied force depends on how the force is applied.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] It is the support force exerted upon an object which is in contact with another stable object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Normal force is sometimes referred to as the pressing force since its action presses the surface together.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Normal force is always directed towards the object and acts perpendicularly with the applied force.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] It is the force exerted by a surface as an object moves across it or makes an effort to move across it.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The friction force opposes the motion of the object.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Friction results when two surfaces are pressed together closely, causing attractive intermolecular forces between the molecules of the two different surface.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] As such, friction depends upon the nature of the two surfaces and upon the degree to which they are pressed together.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Friction always acts parallel to the surface in contact and opposite the direction of motion.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The friction force can be calculated using the equation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] For fixed impulse $\mathbf {j}$ , the equation suggests that $t_{1}\rightarrow t_{0}\Rightarrow \left|\mathbf {f} \right|\rightarrow \infty$ , that is, a smaller time interval must be compensated by a stronger reaction force to achieve the same impulse.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] When modelling a collision between idealized rigid bodies, it is impractical to simulate the compression and expansion phases of the body geometry over the collision time interval.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] exists and is equal to $\mathbf {j}$ , the notion of *instantaneous impulses* may be introduced to simulate an instantaneous change in velocity after a collision.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] By deduction from the principle of action and reaction, if the collision impulse applied by the first body on the second body at a contact point $\mathbf {p} _{r}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ , the counter impulse applied by the second body on the first is $-\mathbf {j} _{r}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] In the subsequent formulas, $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is always assumed to point away from body 1 and towards body 2 at the contact point.
