[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] One of the most popular models for describing friction is the Coulomb friction model.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] This model defines coefficients of static friction ${\mu }_{s}\in \mathbb {R}$ and dynamic friction ${\mu }_{d}\in \mathbb {R}$ such that ${\mu }_{s}>{\mu }_{d}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] These coefficients describe the two types of friction forces in terms of the reaction forces acting on the bodies.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The value $f_{s}$ defines a maximum magnitude for the friction force required to counter the tangential component of any external sum force applied on a relatively static body, such that it remains static.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Thus, if the external force is large enough, static friction is unable to fully counter this force, at which point the body gains velocity and becomes subject to dynamic friction of magnitude $f_{d}$ acting against the sliding velocity.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The Coulomb friction model effectively defines a friction cone within which the tangential component of a force exerted by one body on the surface of another in static contact, is countered by an equal and opposite force such that the static configuration is maintained.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Conversely, if the force falls outside the cone, static friction gives way to dynamic friction.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] where $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the sum of all external forces on the body.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] The multi-case definition of $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ is required for robustly computing the actual friction force $\mathbf {f} _{f}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ for both the general and particular states of contact.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Informally, the first case computes the tangent vector along the relative velocity component perpendicular to the contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] If this component is zero, the second case derives $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ in terms of the tangent component of the external force $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] If there is no tangential velocity or external forces, then no friction is assumed, and $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ may be set to the zero vector.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Equations (6a), (6b), (7) and (8) describe the Coulomb friction model in terms of forces.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] where $j_{r}=|\mathbf {j} _{r}|$ is the magnitude of the reaction impulse acting along contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] Equations (5) and (10) define an impulse-based contact model that is ideal for impulse-based simulations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/collision-response] When using this model, care must be taken in the choice of ${\mu }_{s}$ and ${\mu }_{d}$ as higher values may introduce additional kinetic energy into the system.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In geometry, the **hyperplane separation theorem** is a theorem about disjoint convex sets in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] There are several rather similar versions.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In one version of the theorem, if both these sets are closed and at least one of them is compact, then there is a hyperplane in between them and even two parallel hyperplanes in between them separated by a gap.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In another version, if both disjoint convex sets are open, then there is a hyperplane in between them, but not necessarily any gap.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] An axis which is orthogonal to a separating hyperplane is a **separating axis**, because the orthogonal projections of the convex bodies onto the axis are disjoint.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] The hyperplane separation theorem is due to Hermann Minkowski.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] The Hahn–Banach separation theorem generalizes the result to topological vector spaces.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] A related result is the supporting hyperplane theorem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In the context of support-vector machines, the *optimally separating hyperplane* or *maximum-margin hyperplane* is a hyperplane which separates two sets of points and maximizes its distance to both sets.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] for all x in A and y in B ; i.e., the hyperplane $\langle \cdot ,v\rangle =c$ , v the normal vector, separates A and B .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In all cases, assume $A,B$ to be disjoint, nonempty, and convex subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] The number of dimensions must be finite.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In infinite-dimensional spaces there are examples of two closed, convex, disjoint sets which cannot be separated by a closed hyperplane (a hyperplane where a *continuous* linear functional equals some constant) even in the weak sense where the inequalities are not strict.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Here, the compactness in the hypothesis cannot be relaxed; see an example in the section Counterexamples and uniqueness.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] This version of the separation theorem does generalize to infinite-dimension; the generalization is more commonly known as the Hahn–Banach separation theorem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Let $a\in A$ and $b\in B$ be any pair of points, and let $r_{1}=\|b-a\|$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Since A is compact, it is contained in some ball centered on a ; let the radius of this ball be $r_{2}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Let $S=B\cap {\overline {B_{r_{1}+r_{2}}(a)}}$ be the intersection of B with a closed ball of radius $r_{1}+r_{2}$ around a .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Then S is compact and nonempty because it contains b .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Since the distance function is continuous, there exist points $a_{0}$ and $b_{0}$ whose distance $\|a_{0}-b_{0}\|$ is the minimum over all pairs of points in $A\times S$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] It remains to show that $a_{0}$ and $b_{0}$ in fact have the minimum distance over all pairs of points in $A\times B$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] By the lemma, there exist points $a_{0}\in A$ and $b_{0}\in B$ of minimum distance to each other.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Since A and B are disjoint, we have $a_{0}\neq b_{0}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] We claim that neither A nor B enters the space between $L_{A},L_{B}$ , and thus the perpendicular hyperplanes to $(a_{0},b_{0})$ satisfy the requirement of the theorem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Our claim is that $\forall a\in A,\langle v,a\rangle \leq c_{A}$ and $\forall b\in B,\langle v,b\rangle \geq c_{B}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Suppose for contradiction that there is some point $a\in A$ such that $\langle v,a\rangle >c_{A}$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] So for sufficiently small $\epsilon >0$ , the point $a'=a_{0}+\epsilon (a-a_{0})$ satisfies $f(a')<f(a_{0})$ , which contradicts the choice of $a_{0}$ since $a'\in A$ by convexity.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] A similar argument shows $\forall b\in B,\langle v,b\rangle \geq c_{B}$ .
