[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] in particular, we have the supporting hyperplane theorem.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] If the affine span of A is not all of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , then extend the affine span to a supporting hyperplane.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Note that the existence of a hyperplane that only "separates" two convex sets in the weak sense of both inequalities being non-strict obviously does not imply that the two sets are disjoint.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Both sets could have points located on the hyperplane.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] If one of *A* or *B* is not convex, then there are many possible counterexamples.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] For example, *A* and *B* could be concentric circles.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] A more subtle counterexample is one in which *A* and *B* are both closed but neither one is compact.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] (Although, by an instance of the second theorem, there is a hyperplane that separates their interiors.) Another type of counterexample has *A* compact and *B* open.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] For example, A can be a closed square and B can be an open square that touches *A*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In the first version of the theorem, evidently the separating hyperplane is never unique.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In the second version, it may or may not be unique.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Technically a separating axis is never unique because it can be translated; in the second version of the theorem, a separating axis can be unique up to translation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] The horn angle provides a good counterexample to many hyperplane separations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] For example, in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , the unit disk is disjoint from the open interval $((1,0),(1,1))$ , but the only line separating them contains the entirety of $((1,0),(1,1))$ .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] This shows that if A is closed and B is *relatively* open, then there does not necessarily exist a separation that is strict for B .
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] However, if A is a closed convex polyhedron then such a separation exists.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Farkas' lemma and related results can be understood as hyperplane separation theorems when the convex bodies are defined by finitely many linear inequalities.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Regardless of dimensionality, the separating axis is always a line.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] For example, in 3D, the space is separated by planes, but the separating axis is perpendicular to the separating plane.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] The separating axis theorem can be applied for fast collision detection between polygon meshes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Each face's normal or other feature direction is used as a separating axis.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Note that this yields possible separating axes, not separating lines/planes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] In 3D, using face normals alone will fail to separate some edge-on-edge non-colliding cases.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] Additional axes, consisting of the cross-products of pairs of edges, one taken from each object, are required.
[src:collision-detection-2d/hyperplane-separation-theorem] For increased efficiency, parallel axes may be calculated as a single axis.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] When other kinds of measure are used, the minimum box is usually called accordingly, e.g., "minimum-perimeter bounding box".
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] The minimum bounding box of a point set is the same as the minimum bounding box of its convex hull, a fact which may be used heuristically to speed up computation.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] In the two-dimensional case it is called the *minimum bounding rectangle*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box (or **AABB**) for a given point set is its minimum bounding box subject to the constraint that the edges of the box are parallel to the (Cartesian) coordinate axes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] It is the Cartesian product of *N* intervals each of which is defined by the minimal and maximal value of the corresponding coordinate for the points in *S*.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] Axis-aligned minimal bounding boxes are used as an approximate location of an object in question and as a very simple descriptor of its shape.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] For example, in computational geometry and its applications when it is required to find intersections in the set of objects, the initial check is the intersections between their MBBs.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] Since it is usually a much less expensive operation than the check of the actual intersection (because it only requires comparisons of coordinates), it allows quickly excluding checks of the pairs that are far apart.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] The arbitrarily oriented minimum bounding box is the minimum bounding box, calculated subject to no constraints as to the orientation of the result.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] A three-dimensional rotating calipers algorithm can find the minimum-volume arbitrarily-oriented bounding box of a three-dimensional point set in cubic time.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] Matlab implementations of the latter as well as the optimal compromise between accuracy and CPU time are available.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] In the case where an object has its own local coordinate system, it can be useful to store a bounding box relative to these axes, which requires no transformation as the object's own transformation changes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/minimum-bounding-box] In digital image processing, the *bounding box* is merely the coordinates of the rectangular border that fully encloses a digital image when it is placed over a page, a canvas, a screen or other similar bidimensional background.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] In physical simulations, **sweep and prune** is a broad phase algorithm used during collision detection to limit the number of pairs of solids that need to be checked for collision, i.e. intersection.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] This is achieved by sorting the starts (lower bound) and ends (upper bound) of the bounding volume of each solid along a number of arbitrary axes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] As the solids move, their starts and ends may overlap.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] When the bounding volumes of two solids overlap in all axes they are flagged to be tested by more precise and time-consuming algorithms.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Sweep and prune exploits temporal coherence as it is likely that solids do not move significantly between two simulation steps.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Because of that, at each step, the sorted lists of bounding volume starts and ends can be updated with relatively few computational operations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Sorting algorithms which are fast at sorting almost-sorted lists, such as insertion sort, are particularly good for this purpose.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] According with the type of bounding volume used, it is necessary to update the bounding volume dimensions every time a solid is reoriented.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] To circumvent this, temporal coherence can be used to compute the changes in bounding volume geometry with fewer operations.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Another approach is to use bounding spheres or other orientation independent bounding volumes.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Sweep and prune is also known as *sort and sweep*, referred to this way in David Baraff's Ph.D. thesis in 1992.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Later works like the 1995 paper about I-COLLIDE by Jonathan D.
[src:collision-detection-2d/sweep-and-prune] Cohen *et al.* refer to the algorithm as *sweep and prune*.
